{#def title="Minds", is_mac=None, is_authenticated=False, mngr_forward_origin=None, is_agent_content_surface=False, body_class="", body_style="", head="", scripts="", initial_accent="" #}
{#
  Shared trusted app shell: the fixed titlebar + browser-mode floating sidebar
  + accent / chrome.js wiring, wrapping a page body passed in the content slot.

  This is the trusted app chrome. Two modes:

  - Local page (default, ``is_agent_content_surface=False``): a trusted
    local/native page (Landing, Create, Settings, ...) renders its own body in
    the slot, wrapped in the ``#local-page-card`` -- an inset rounded card shaped
    exactly like the workspace content surface -- which is the page's scroll
    container. The accent-tracking body bleeds around the card just like around
    a workspace.
  - Agent content surface (``is_agent_content_surface=True``): pages.Chrome
    fills the slot with the content iframe (the browser-mode agent surface).

  In both modes the document is locked to the viewport (``overflow: hidden``)
  and the body background tracks ``--titlebar-bg`` so an active workspace accent
  (or the neutral chrome) bleeds through the content card's insets and rounded
  corners.

  ``is_mac`` (traffic-light spacer + hidden window controls) and
  ``mngr_forward_origin`` (the body data attribute chrome.js reads to build
  ``/goto/<agent>/`` links) default to the live-request catalog globals so a
  trusted page need not thread them through its render function; pages.Chrome
  passes them explicitly. In Electron mode the browser-mode sidebar block is
  hidden via JS; the content is a separate WebContentsView and window.minds
  exposes IPC adapters. ``head`` / ``scripts`` let a page append its own head
  tags / script tags after the shell's own (workspace_accent.js,
  backup_health.js, sidebar_workspace_row.js, chrome.js).

  ``title`` is rendered into the visible titlebar (``#page-title``) as well as the
  document title, so the first paint shows the real title rather than a hardcoded
  placeholder that chrome.js then rewrites. ``initial_accent`` (a ``#rrggbb``, when
  the workspace is known at render time) seeds the titlebar's background AND
  foreground-contrast (``.titlebar-surface``) on the first frame -- see the head /
  titlebar blocks below.
#}
{% set _is_mac = is_mac if is_mac is not none else chrome_is_mac() %}
{% set _mngr_forward_origin = mngr_forward_origin if mngr_forward_origin is not none else chrome_mngr_forward_origin() %}
{# Both modes lock the document to the viewport and track --titlebar-bg on the
   body, so the workspace accent (or the neutral chrome) bleeds around the inset
   content card: the content WebContentsView / #content-frame iframe on the agent
   surface, the #local-page-card wrapper (below) on local pages. Local pages
   scroll INSIDE that card, not the document. #}
{% set _body_class = body_class if body_class else "font-sans antialiased" %}
{% set _body_style = body_style if body_style else "background-color: var(--titlebar-bg, var(--c-surface-primary));" %}
{# The document never scrolls in either mode (the card / content view scrolls),
   so both opt out of the global stable scrollbar gutter -- otherwise classic
   scrollbars reserve a dead 15px strip on an edge-to-edge locked surface. #}
{% set _html_class = "no-scrollbar-gutter" %}
{% set _head %}
<style>
  /* Things that can't easily be expressed as Tailwind utilities. */
  html, body { height: 100%; overflow: hidden; }
  #minds-titlebar { -webkit-app-region: drag; }
  #minds-titlebar button { -webkit-app-region: no-drag; }
  /* When the inbox modal (or any modal hosted in the main process's
     modalView) is open, drop the titlebar's app-region: drag. macOS
     unions drag regions across all views in a window, so without this
     the titlebar's drag swallows clicks intended for the modal's
     interior in the y=0..TITLEBAR strip. The main process sends
     `modal-state-changed` over IPC and chrome.js toggles the
     ``modal-open`` body class accordingly. */
  body.modal-open #minds-titlebar { -webkit-app-region: no-drag; }
</style>
{%- if initial_accent %}
{# Seed the workspace accent on :root before chrome.js runs so the first paint of
   a freshly (re)loaded wrapper already carries it (the titlebar background AND --
   via the .titlebar-surface class below -- its contrasting foreground). chrome.js's
   later documentElement.style set (same value) overrides this rule seamlessly. #}
<style>:root { --titlebar-bg: {{ initial_accent }}; }</style>
{%- endif %}
{%- if head %}
{{ head }}
{%- endif %}
{% endset %}
{% set _body_attrs %}data-is-mac="{{ 'true' if _is_mac else 'false' }}" data-is-authenticated="{{ 'true' if is_authenticated else 'false' }}" data-mngr-forward-origin="{{ _mngr_forward_origin }}"{% endset %}
{% set _scripts %}
<script src="/_static/workspace_accent.js" defer></script>
<script src="/_static/backup_health.js" defer></script>
<script src="/_static/sidebar_workspace_row.js" defer></script>
<script src="/_static/chrome.js" defer></script>
{%- if scripts %}
{{ scripts }}
{%- endif %}
{% endset %}
<Base :title="title"
      :html_class="_html_class"
      :body_class="_body_class"
      :body_style="_body_style"
      head={{ _head }}
      body_attrs={{ _body_attrs }}
      scripts={{ _scripts }}>
  {# Three flex sections sized 1 / 2 / 1 so the page title always sits in the
     screen's exact center, regardless of how wide each side's controls are.
     Centering holds only while the left and right ``flex-1`` sections stay
     equal width, so macOS reserves the traffic-light strip with a fixed
     spacer div -- NOT a left padding. With ``box-sizing: border-box`` a left
     padding clamps the section's flex base size up to that padding, making the
     left section 72px wider than the right and shoving the title ~36px
     off-center to the right. A ``shrink-0`` spacer instead lives inside the
     section, which ``min-w-0`` lets shrink to its 1/4 flex share, so both
     sides keep equal width and the center stays truly centered. Non-mac draws
     its own min/max/close at the right. #}
  {# ``titlebar-surface`` (foreground-contrast re-basing off --titlebar-bg) is
     seeded here when an accent is known at render time so the icons/text paint
     with the right contrast on the first frame; chrome.js keeps toggling it as the
     accent changes. #}
  <div id="minds-titlebar"
       style="background-color: var(--titlebar-bg, var(--c-surface-primary));"
       class="fixed top-0 left-0 right-0 h-[38px] flex items-center select-none z-[100] px-1{% if initial_accent %} titlebar-surface{% endif %}">
    <div class="flex-1 flex items-center gap-0.5 min-w-0">
      {% if _is_mac %}<div class="w-[72px] shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"></div>{% endif %}
      <TitlebarButton id="sidebar-toggle" aria-label="Main Menu" data-tooltip="Main Menu"><Icon16 name="menu" /></TitlebarButton>
      <TitlebarButton id="home-btn" aria-label="Home" data-tooltip="Home"><Icon16 name="home" /></TitlebarButton>
      <TitlebarButton id="back-btn" aria-label="Back" data-tooltip="Back"><Icon16 name="chevron-left" /></TitlebarButton>
      <TitlebarButton id="forward-btn" aria-label="Forward" data-tooltip="Forward"><Icon16 name="chevron-right" /></TitlebarButton>
    </div>
    <div class="flex-[2] flex items-center justify-center px-2 min-w-0">
      {# Rendered inline (from the same value that becomes the document title) so
         the first paint shows the real title instead of a hardcoded "Minds" that
         chrome.js then rewrites. chrome.js keeps it in sync on later navigations. #}
      <span id="page-title" class="text-primary type-label whitespace-nowrap overflow-hidden text-ellipsis">{{ title }}</span>
    </div>
    <div class="flex-1 flex items-center justify-end min-w-0">
      <TitlebarButton id="help-toggle" aria-label="Ran into a bug?" data-tooltip="Ran into a bug?"><Icon16 name="bug" /></TitlebarButton>
      <TitlebarButton id="requests-toggle" aria-label="Requests" data-tooltip="Requests" extra="gap-[3px]">
        <Icon16 name="inbox" />
        <Badge :count="0" id="requests-badge" hidden />
      </TitlebarButton>
      <div class="flex {% if _is_mac %}hidden{% endif %}">
        <TitlebarButton variant="control" id="min-btn" aria-label="Minimize" data-tooltip="Minimize"><Icon12 name="minimize" /></TitlebarButton>
        <TitlebarButton variant="control" id="max-btn" aria-label="Maximize" data-tooltip="Maximize"><Icon12 name="maximize" /></TitlebarButton>
        <TitlebarButton variant="control" tone="danger" id="close-btn" aria-label="Close" data-tooltip="Close"><Icon12 name="close" /></TitlebarButton>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  {# Browser-mode floating sidebar: full-screen transparent backdrop
     (#sidebar-backdrop) with a floating dark menu (#sidebar-menu)
     positioned at toggle time by chrome.js using the sidebar-toggle
     button's getBoundingClientRect + a caller-chosen offset. Clicks on
     the backdrop and Escape close the menu (handled by chrome.js). In
     Electron this whole block is hidden via JS; the sidebar page
     (Sidebar.jinja) is loaded into the shared modal WebContentsView and
     uses the same #sidebar-backdrop / #sidebar-menu shape with the
     /_static/sidebar.js renderer. Both modes share the position model:
     menu.top-left = trigger.bottom-left + offset, with a uniform 4px panel
     pad (p-1) and 2px between entries (gap-0.5); each row adds its own
     px-2 for the hover highlight's inset. #}
  <div id="sidebar-backdrop" class="fixed inset-0 z-50 hidden">
    <div id="sidebar-menu"
         class="dark absolute w-[280px] flex flex-col gap-0.5 p-1 rounded-lg border border-subtle bg-surface-primary shadow-overlay overflow-hidden">
      <div id="sidebar-workspaces" class="flex flex-col gap-0.5"></div>
      <SidebarBottom />
    </div>
  </div>

  {% if is_agent_content_surface %}
  {{ content }}
  {% else %}
  {# Local pages render inside a card shaped exactly like the workspace content
     surface (left/right 4px, top 38px, bottom 4px insets + 12px radius --
     matches CONTENT_INSET / CONTENT_CORNER_RADIUS in electron/main.js and the
     agent wrapper's #content-frame), so the accent-tracking body bleeds around
     it just like around a workspace. The card is the scroll container; pages
     that center vertically wrap their content in ``min-h-full`` (the card has a
     definite height, so percentage heights resolve). #}
  <div id="local-page-card"
       class="fixed left-[4px] top-[38px] rounded-[12px] bg-surface-primary text-primary overflow-y-auto"
       style="width: calc(100% - 8px); height: calc(100% - 42px); box-shadow: 0 1px 0 rgba(255,255,255,0.05) inset;">
    {{ content }}
  </div>
  {% endif %}
</Base>
